Like sometimes faster than one per minute he would rattle off new program ideas. It created a kind of gridlock and it never goes down. But it did slow under Clinton. More than it did under Reagan, more than it did under the two Bushes, and certainly more than it has under Obama. There's something to be said for the fact that yes, he was distracted by Monica Wenske and the blue dress and all of that. And wound up in his second term. Being a foreign policy president like all the ones in the past have been in their second terms where they can't get anything through Congress. And yeah, he did bad things then because now we're lobbing bombs at aspirin factories in Iraq and we're getting involved in air wars in Kosovo. But domestically he couldn't get his agenda through and that's why in retrospect he succeeded, because he failed. And in fairness to the Clintons, I suppose they do have a lot of corporatist instincts as opposed to socialist instincts and sometimes that's a slight improvement. I think in some ways Hillary Clinton will be the culmination of the whole hundred year progressive plan in that if you look back at the original progressives, they didn't think of themselves as full fledged socialists, they really did want a partnership between big government and big business. And talk about that. It took a while but they got it. They won. Oh well. Well, several things. I'm curious about how Todd would distinguish the progressives from the interwar fascists. I mean my impression is that there's definitely a distinction between the left progressives and the right fascists. And exactly how that plays itself out in history I don't entirely understand. But there's something Franklin said that I thought was really interesting about the Clinton years that the freedom such as it was of the 90s came about not because anybody intended it but because there was a gridlock that nobody's agenda could get passed because there was too much conflict and they were canceling each other out. And as a result, the result was a lower budget deficit, some increases in freedom, there was welfare reform and otherwise. And it made me, your comment triggered something in my mind. I think that sometimes libertarians forget the history of liberty itself which is not that, it's not that like in Europe in the 16th, 17th century anybody came to power for who believed in liberty. The reason that we got liberty, I'm drawing here mainly on Ralph Franco and some of my other teachers, the reason we had liberty was not because anybody intended it, it's because there was a competition between powers and they checked each other.
